er military decision-making and clarifies the role law played—where it constrained action, where it was manipulated, where it was ignored, and how it developed in combat—in each case. A Scrap of Paper is a passionate defense of the role that the law must play to govern interstate relations in both peace and war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHumanitarian lawxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar (International law)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xLaw and legislation. 4aHistory. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aBegian neutrality, submarine warfare, interstate relations, peace, war, military.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147065340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470653/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles